The Prompt:

Help me design a meal prep plan for 6 meals, total calories of 5400. Other requirements Please make all the foods anti-inflammatory, no eggs , but add salmon, ground beef 
over the course of a week. Provide a list of all anti inflammatory foods and a calorie count after each meal

The Result: 

Creating a meal prep plan that includes six meals with a total of 5,400 calories while focusing on anti-inflammatory foods, excluding eggs but including salmon and ground beef over the course of a week can be a healthy and nutritious way to approach your meals. Here's a sample meal plan, along with anti-inflammatory foods and calorie counts for each meal:

Day 1:
Meal 1: Breakfast - 800 calories

Scrambled tofu with spinach, mushrooms, and turmeric (350 calories)
1/2 avocado (120 calories)
Fresh berries (strawberries, blueberries) (100 calories)
1 slice of whole-grain toast (100 calories)
Green tea (30 calories)
Meal 2: Lunch - 700 calories

Grilled salmon with a side of quinoa (400 calories)
Steamed broccoli and carrots (150 calories)
Mixed greens salad with olive oil and balsamic vinegar (150 calories)
Meal 3: Dinner - 750 calories

Lean ground beef stir-fry with colorful bell peppers and broccoli (400 calories)
Brown rice (150 calories)
Sliced cucumbers and tomatoes with a tahini dressing (200 calories)
Day 2:
Meal 4: Breakfast - 800 calories

Chia pudding made with almond milk, topped with fresh mango and pomegranate seeds (400 calories)
Almonds (200 calories)
Green tea (30 calories)
Anti-inflammatory spices (e.g., ginger, cinnamon)
Meal 5: Lunch - 700 calories

Baked sweet potato with black beans and a dollop of guacamole (400 calories)
Steamed kale (100 calories)
Mixed berry smoothie with anti-inflammatory spices (200 calories)
Meal 6: Dinner - 750 calories

Baked or grilled salmon with a lemon-dill sauce (400 calories)
Quinoa and asparagus (150 calories)
Mixed greens salad with walnuts and an olive oil and lemon dressing (200 calories)
Throughout the week, make sure to incorporate a variety of anti-inflammatory foods, including:

Fatty fish like salmon
Berries (blueberries, strawberries)
Leafy greens (spinach, kale)
Colorful vegetables (bell peppers, carrots, broccoli, asparagus)
Tofu or tempeh
Legumes (black beans)
Nuts and seeds (almonds, walnuts, chia seeds)
Whole grains (quinoa, brown rice)
Anti-inflammatory spices (turmeric, ginger, cinnamon)
Healthy fats (avocado, olive oil)
Please note that the above meal plan is just a starting point and can be adjusted to suit your taste preferences and dietary needs. It's important to consult with a healthcare professional or nutritionist for personalized guidance on meal plans, especially if you have specific dietary restrictions or health concerns. Additionally, the calorie counts are approximate, and you can adjust portion sizes to meet your daily caloric goals.
